original: Jonsson, Carl Axel Sven, tandläkare, Jönköping, f. 4/10/70 i Linköp. av juveler. C. J. J. o. Ehn Maria Larsson. G. 96 m. Ruth Hildegard Söderberg, d. 37. Barn: Einar f. 97, Elsa 98, d. 30, Margit 99, Ruth 02, Karl Axel 05, d. 38, Bo 09, d. 34, Anna Marie 11. — Mog:ex. i Linköp. 90, elev v. Gbgs tan-dl :inst. s. å., tandi :kiand. 91, tand-läk. 92. Assist, v. poliklin. f. tand-sjukd. i Berlin 93, praktik i Jönköp.’ sed. 93. Styr:led. i Sv:es tandhförb. 15-20, en av stift, av samt ordf. 12-31 i Smål tandi :fören. V. ordf. i Jönköp. folksk:styr. 07-20, led. av stadsfullm. sed. 24, av drätselkamm. under sex år, ordf. i styr. f. stadsbibi samt i Fören. Fysisk fostran, led. av styr. f. translated: Jonsson, Carl Axel Sven, dentist, from Jönköping, born on October 4th, 1870 in Linköping to Juveler. His parents were C. J. J. and Ehn Maria Larsson. He married Ruth Hildegard Söderberg in 1896, who passed away in 1937. They had eight children: Einar born in 1897, Elsa born in 1898 and passed away in 1930, Margit born in 1899, Ruth born in 1902, Karl Axel born in 1905 and passed away in 1938, Bo born in 1909 and passed away in 1934, and Anna Marie born in 1911. He passed the dental exam in Linköping in 1890, was a student at Gothenburg Dentistry Institute the same year, and became a dentist in 1892. He worked as an assistant at the dental clinic for dental diseases in Berlin in 1893 and established his practice in Jönköping in the same year. Jonsson was a board member for the Swedish Dental Association from 1915-1920 and was one of the founders as well as chairperson for the Småland Dental Association from 1912-1931. He was the vice chairperson of the Jönköping People's School Board from 1907-1920, a member of the city council since 1924, and served on the city finance committee for six years. Jonsson was the chairperson of the board for the City Library and the Association for Physical Education and a member of the board for A-B Gothenburg's Handbank’s branch office. He was awarded Knight of the Royal Order of Vasa (RVO) and the Swedish Red Cross Medal.
